[4] Modeling comment
Date: 17 Jan 2015
From: Gregory Kelly <gka25@sfu.ca> [excerpted, edited]


Regarding ProMED post "Ebola update (16): vaccine, models, slowing, transmission, nurse, malaria, susp 20150117.3098295, I very respectfully disagree with Mod.JW's comments about the futility of modeling Ebola due to inaccurate data. True, there is a lot of basis for "garbage in, garbage out," but mathematical and computational modeling is more than just predictions and numbers. What modeling can reveal are patterns and relationships within the system well in advance of statistical analysis done after the fact.

One key element in mathematical models known as "compartmental models" (also known as "S-I-R" models) is the ability to calculate algebraically the location of the "transcritical bifurcation," or tipping point from where the "disease-free equilibrium" is no longer stable and an epidemic would likely occur with the introduction of an infected host into the community. This algebraic point does not need absolute numbers but rather variables that reflect parameters in the model. This allows us to examine in advance the influence of the individual parameters, which may occur non-linearly, something that often troubles statistical analysis based on linear regression. This tipping point is usually the square of R0 (the number of secondary infections from a single infection introduced into an entirely susceptible community), which means we can directly calculate R0 if we do have accurate numbers, and if we don't, we can feed in a range of parameter values to get some expectation of how bad the epidemic might be... From what I can tell, the data on HCW [health care workers] illnesses and outcomes are likely to be the most accurate; the rest can be modeled over a range of possibilities...

Another aspect of compartmental models is that with some effort, we can get numerical solutions for how the system is likely to decay back to the disease-free equilibrium... There are some challenges to compartmental models; they are deterministic, they can have biases that might not reflect the true dynamics of the system, and in order to make them manageable mathematically, they may contain simplifications that diminish their accuracy (biases and simplifications are not the same thing)... Over tens of thousands or even millions of simulated runs, patterns can emerge that can help inform resource allocation.

I would not dispute that some of the Ebola projections now seem overly pessimistic, but we have to keep in mind that those projections were based on a fairly static system - i.e., what would have happened if nothing was done. Mathematical and computational modeling can help disprove the negative in policy decision-making (if we had done nothing, it wouldn't have been bad anyways, so allocating resources for prevention is a waste of money)...

[Gregory (Tim) Kelly is a PhD student at Simon Fraser University in Burnaby, British Columbia (Canada) studying mathematical models of diseases and a sponsored member of the Interdisciplinary Research in the Mathematical and Computational Sciences Centre founded by the mathematician Dr. Peter Borwein, who is one of Gregory's committee members.]

--
Gregory (Tim) Kelly
<gka25@sfu.ca>

[I encourage interested readers to contact Tim to receive his letter in full.

But: "If we don't (have accurate numbers), we can feed in a range of parameter values..." And come up with what? guesses? We won't even be able to put confidence intervals on the results, or they would be so wide as to be meaningless. - Mod.JW]

